{"tid":1839494,"cid":5,"subCid":10,"title":"林鄭瑞士開會sell香港 以點心宴客顯香港特色","createTime":"2020-01-24T12:35:38.000Z","updateTime":"2020-01-24T19:57:44.000Z","uid":133680,"like":11,"dislike":172,"uniUserReply":78,"replies":[{"pid":"8f0f4a32e6dc01d9a4bc8cb186223e3bacfee702","tid":1839494,"uid":133680,"like":0,"dislike":0,"score":0,"citedBy":0,"replyTime":"2020-01-24T12:35:38.000Z","msg":"<a href=\"https://www.bloomberg.com/news/articles/2020-01-24/carrie-lam-courts-davos-elites-with-dim-sum-to-sell-hong-kong?srnd=premium-asia\" data-sr-url=\"https://r.lihkg.com/link?u=https%3A%2F%2Fwww.bloomberg.com%2Fnews%2Farticles%2F2020-01-24%2Fcarrie-lam-courts-davos-elites-with-dim-sum-to-sell-hong-kong%3Fsrnd%3Dpremium-asia&d=3ovy23W4cNvxoMUnqPf77SK1%2BumEGLY4xtueqN3WuFY%3D&h=4afb6d4b\" data-auto-link target=\"_blank\">https://www.bloomberg.com/news/articles/2020-01-24/carrie-lam-courts-davos-elites-with-dim-sum-to-sell-hong-kong?srnd=premium-asia</a><br />\nSkip to content<br />\n<br />\n<br />\n2020年1月24日 上午5:39 [GMT+1]<br />\nChief executive hosts party at World Economic Forum in Davos<br />\nCity in throes of political unrest, confronts new virus<br />\n<br />\nChina Wants Hong Kong to Succeed Under 'One Country, Two Systems,' Says Lam<br />\nUnmute<br />\nLam says China wants Hong Kong to succeed under &quot;One Country, Two Systems&quot;<br />\nSHARE THIS ARTICLE<br />\n<br />\nCarrie Lam hosted 200 business and political leaders for dim sum and cocktails at a Swiss ski resort Thursday to reassure them that Hong Kong&rsquo;s future is bright. It was a tough sell.<br />\n<br />\nThe city&rsquo;s leader told the crowd gathered at the World Economic Forum in Davos that Hong Kong was still open for business, despite paralyzing protests and an economy in recession. She also said that officials back home were working to contain the coronavirus that&rsquo;s killed more than two dozen people in China and infected hundreds of others. Hong Kong has identified two cases.<br />\n<br />\nOpening Day Of The World Economic Forum (WEF) 2020<br />\nCarrie Lam in Davos, Jan. 21.<br />\nIn a room decorated with gold candles and red Chinese lanterns for Lunar New Year, Lam said her government &ldquo;will safeguard Hong Kong&rsquo;s fundamentals, including the rule of law.&rdquo; She was also &ldquo;fully confident of the city&rsquo;s future,&rdquo; according to a readout from her office.<br />\n<br />\nJoining about 30 government officials at the &ldquo;Hong Kong Night&rdquo; in Davos were heads of the city&rsquo;s stock exchange, airport and mass transit train operator. The chairmen of conglomerates Swire Pacific and Far East Consortium International also spoke at the event held in a restaurant overlooking the Alps.<br />\n<br />\nLam&rsquo;s overseas charm offensive had already included a splashy marketing and ad campaign in global media outlets. At Davos, she gave a series of television interviews and also met the prime ministers of Luxembourg, Singapore and the Netherlands, as well as the heads of the International Monetary Fund and Julius Baer Group.<br />\n<br />\nXi Isn&rsquo;t Tightening China&rsquo;s Grip on Hong Kong, Carrie Lam Says<br />\n<br />\n&ldquo;Ultimately to take Hong Kong out of the economic difficulties requires first of all stability,&rdquo; she told Bloomberg Television. &ldquo;Secondly it&rsquo;s an early restoration of law and order, and thirdly it&rsquo;s continued government investment in important sectors &ndash; for example, innovation and technology.&rdquo;"},{"pid":"bc2961a94da909e4ae700c26450a6d8885b08904","tid":1839494,"uid":133680,"like":3,"dislike":19,"score":-16,"citedBy":0,"replyTime":"2020-01-24T12:36:00.000Z","msg":"Not everyone was buying what Lam was selling. Yuan Ding, vice president of China Europe International Business School and a Davos delegate, said it was unclear what power Lam had to make critical decisions that could end the unrest that began last June.<br />\nShare Tweet Post Email<br />\nSingapore&rsquo;s Prime Minister Lee Hsien Loong says the &ldquo;one country, two systems&rdquo; principle that governs Hong Kong may not last unless the government makes progress on protester concerns over the lack of affordable housing in the Asian financial hub.<br />\n<br />\nIn an interview with Bloomberg&rsquo;s Editor-in-Chief John Micklethwait on the sidelines of the World Economic Forum in Davos, Lee said he sympathizes with Hong Kong protesters, but doesn&rsquo;t see how their methods -- which have included violent rallies, petrol bombs and vandalism -- will resolve their problems. Hong Kong youth are frustrated by the world&rsquo;s most expensive housing market and the fact that Hong Kong has dwindled in importance to China as mainland cities have become richer, he said.<br />\n<br />\nDay Three Of The World Economic Forum (WEF) 2020<br />\nLee Hsien Loong<br />\n&ldquo;I can understand the issues which lead people in Hong Kong to feel anxiety and frustration and disappointment at what the future holds for them,&rdquo; Lee said, noting the median price of a dwelling in Hong Kong now costs 21 times the annual salary. &ldquo;But I can&rsquo;t see how this path is going to lead to improvements in all of these difficult problems.&rdquo;<br />\n<br />\nLee, who last year criticized Hong Kong&rsquo;s protesters at a conference for making unrealistic demands and trying to &ldquo;humiliate and bring down the government,&rdquo; said Hong Kong authorities nevertheless need to act on economic grievances that underpin the protests.<br />\n<br />\nAlthough many demonstrators say they are fighting for greater democracy rather than for cheaper housing, some -- including Hong Kong Chief Executive Carrie Lam -- have pointed to a lack of affordable housing and inequality as key factors in the city&rsquo;s unrest."},{"pid":"9cce7654c68734c9d40711fac9d60c6c6dc13731","tid":1839494,"uid":133680,"like":1,"dislike":16,"score":-15,"citedBy":0,"replyTime":"2020-01-24T12:36:11.000Z","msg":"Singapore&rsquo;s leader said the lack of a house or even a space to call one&rsquo;s own was a &ldquo;basic hygiene issue, it&rsquo;s not a higher-order one.&rdquo;<br />\n<br />\nLee said China&rsquo;s 50-year promise to guarantee Hong Kong separate freedoms under the &ldquo;one country, two systems&rdquo; principle after its return to Chinese rule in 1997 was at risk if the local government did not act.<br />\n<br />\n&ldquo;Ideally, at some point, as the temperature comes down and people cool down, it is possible for the Hong Kong government to make progress on some of the basic issues&rdquo; that bug the protesters, he said.<br />\n<br />\n&ldquo;It&rsquo;s very hard -- I mean they&rsquo;ve tried to, but they haven&rsquo;t succeeded,&rdquo; Lee added. &ldquo;But if they don&rsquo;t make some progress, it&rsquo;s hard to see how &lsquo;one country, two systems&rsquo; can work for another&rdquo; 27 years.<br />\n<br />\n<br />\n&ldquo;The effort made by Carrie Lam and the Hong Kong delegates here to assure the international business community will not work -- they are merely putting on a show,&rdquo; he said. &ldquo;Foreign investors also don&rsquo;t buy this.&rdquo;<br />\n<br />\nMoody&rsquo;s downgraded the credit rating of Hong Kong Monday, citing the &ldquo;absence of an effective response by Hong Kong&rsquo;s executive and legislative branches of government.&rdquo; The Hong Kong government rejected that assessment, saying the downgrade ignored the city&rsquo;s strong fundamentals. A lower rating could give lead to higher business and government borrowing costs, and follows a similar downgrade by Fitch Ratings.<br />\n<br />\nRumors have persisted for months that Beijing may replace Lam, whose approval rating is hovering near a record low of 14%, according to a Hong Kong Public Opinion Program survey. Lam told Bloomberg she would do her &ldquo;utmost to stay in this position to help arrest the current situation.&rdquo;<br />\n<br />\nChinese President Xi Jinping has so far maintained his support for Lam, despite Beijing replacing its main representative in Hong Kong with an official who quickly called for enacting controversial national security legislation.<br />\n<br />\n&ldquo;When it comes to modern communications, whatever your product - a mobile, a dishwasher, a city and its governance &ndash;- the claims you&rsquo;re making about it have to be able to withstand scrutiny,&rdquo; said Marc Sparrow, general manager of Hoffman Agency, a global public relations firm, in Hong Kong. &ldquo;It&rsquo;s open to question whether Carrie Lam&rsquo;s Davos comments pass this test.&rdquo;<br />\n<br />\n&mdash; With assistance by Iain Marlow"},{"pid":"fb8c289f34b72f309baa994aa7c090f3b71f7185","tid":1839494,"uid":54264,"like":159,"dislike":0,"score":159,"citedBy":0,"replyTime":"2020-01-24T12:37:08.000Z","msg":"朱門酒肉臭，路有凍死骨"},{"pid":"bcdd42cf73ed848316c13aa547a0b0f99445ac6c","tid":1839494,"uid":88937,"like":43,"dislike":0,"score":43,"citedBy":0,"replyTime":"2020-01-24T12:37:45.000Z","msg":"賴死唔返香港"},{"pid":"6a8f776fc731d56934f33b87f0728ae905aa8911","tid":1839494,"uid":162008,"like":9,"dislike":1,"score":8,"citedBy":0,"replyTime":"2020-01-24T12:39:43.000Z","msg":"離哂地<br />\n<br />\n<br />\n<br />\n<span style=\"font-size: large;\"><span style=\"font-size: x-large;\"><span style=\"color: red;\">要話俾醫護知，無論你地決定係點，市民會支持你地</span></span><br />\n<br />\n原Post<br />\n<br />\n<span style=\"font-size: x-large;\"><span style=\"color: green;\">大家支唔支持醫護大罷工？</span></span><br />\n<br />\n<span style=\"color: red;\">入黎幫手推十次</span><br />\n<br />\n<a href=\"https://lih.kg/1837575\" data-auto-link target=\"_blank\">https://lih.kg/1837575</a><br />\n- 分享自 LIHKG 討論區<br />\n</span>"},{"pid":"b22c4f98b6f982962637546bcbe395069e2e7cb6","tid":1839494,"uid":136457,"like":72,"dislike":0,"score":72,"citedBy":2,"replyTime":"2020-01-24T12:41:24.000Z","msg":"幾時serve 蝙蝠sell中國"},{"pid":"6137af9c0963c94874fade5fd20f677b0b58b321","tid":1839494,"uid":133680,"like":0,"dislike":1